        "type": "{{ (rulegroup | string).split('_')[0] }}"
  },
  "annotations": {
    "summary": "Number of TCP connections in CLOSE_WAIT state is abnormally high.",
    "description": "üßê **Why This Happens**\n- Application failed to close sockets properly after remote side closed connection.\n- Bugs in application code causing resource leaks.\n- Improperly configured keepalive settings.\n- Load balancer or middleware not handling session termination correctly.\n\nüîç **Impact**\n- File descriptor exhaustion (ulimit) leading to new connection failures.\n- Increased memory usage.\n- Application slowdown or outage if limit is hit.\n\n‚úÖ **Immediate Actions for Ops**\n1. **Check number of CLOSE_WAIT connections:**\n   ```\n   netstat -an | grep CLOSE_WAIT | wc -l\n   ```\n2. Identify offending processes:\n   ```\n   lsof -iTCP -sTCP:CLOSE-WAIT | awk '{print $1,$2,$9}' | sort | uniq -c | sort -nr | head\n   ```\n3. Inspect application logs for connection handling issues.\n4. Check ulimit for open files:\n   ```\n   ulimit -n\n   ```\n5. If count grows continuously:\n   - Restart the impacted application service.\n   - Engage the application team for code-level fix.\n6. Apply proper socket timeout settings and connection cleanup in app code.\n\n‚ö† **Note:** This alert triggers if `tcp_closewait` remains above **100** for 5 minutes."
  },
  "isPaused": false
}

